> How to incorporate jQuery into websites

https://developers.google.com/speed/libraries#jquery
add the first snippet from this library ABOVE your js script in html (as follows)

  <body>
  
  <h1>Hello.</h1>
  
      <script src="https://ajax.googleapis.com/ajax/libs/jquery/3.7.1/jquery.min.js"></script>
      <script src="index.js" charset="utf-8"></script>
  </body>

this will then allow the following jQuery command to change the h1 text to red

  $("h1").css("color", "red");

> Console logging to find something out. 
You could put the following in the js file, and when you open the web page it'll show the colour of the h1. 
Can do the same for something like font-size

  console.log($("h1").css("color"));
  
  $("button");

> If you have a SINGLE property, for example below, then you're getting the value

  console.log($("h1").css("color"));

> If you have two properties, you are setting the value

  $("h1").css("color", "red");

> In general, keep the JavaScript code all about behaviour, style code about appearance and HTML all about content.

So instead of using js as above, you can do the following:
Add a class into your styles.css

  .big-title {
      font-size: 10rem;
      color: yellow;
      font-family: cursive;
  }

Then add this class into your jQuery as follows:
  
  $("h1").addClass("big-title")
  
  $("button");

> Just as you can add class, you can also remove class in the console log as follows:

  $("h1").removeClass("big-title");

> You can also add or remove multiple classes

This in your styles.css
  
  .big-title {
      font-size: 10rem;
      color: yellow;
      font-family: cursive;
  }
  
  .margin-50 {
      margin: 50px;
  }

This in your JavaScript

  $("h1").addClass("big-title margin-50");
  
  $("button");

> You can see whether or not a particular element has a class by console logging

$("h1").hasClass("margin-50");

> Manipulating Text with jQuery

Do the following to add the new text (the text in parenthesis will be the new text)

  $("h1").text("bye");

  $("button").text("don't click me");

Or you can add some html:

  $("button").html("<em></em>");

> Manipulating Attributes with jQuery

Attributes are things like <img src="image"> & <a href="link"></a>

  $("img").attr("src");

Example

 $("img").attr("");

To get AND set:

  $("a").attr("href", "https://www.yahoo.com");

A class is also an HTML Attribute.

> Add Event Listeners with jQuery

  $("h1").click(function() {
    $("h1").css("color", "purple");
  });

For buttons:

  $("button").click(function() {
    $("h1").css("color", "purple");
  });

For Keypress Event:

  $("input").keypress(function(event) {
    console.log(event.key);
  });

> Challenge: Update the code so whenever a key is pressed inside it shows in the h1

  $(document).keypress(function(event) {
    $("h1").text(event.key);
  });

> More flexible way to adding an event listener

  $("h1").on("mouseover", function () {
    $("h1").css("color", "purple");
  });

> Adding & Removing Elements with jQuery

Using the following gives you control over where your code goes:
  before() - adds before your parenthesis
  after() - adds after your parenthesis
  prepend() - adds just before the content of the h1, and after the opening tag
  append() - adds after the content of the h1, but inside the h1 element

You can also remove elements with the following:
  $("button").remove();

